<section xml:id="s_derivatives">
  <title>Derivative of a function</title>


  <definition xml:id="d_differentiable_on_domain">
    <title>Differentiable functions</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> be a real-valued function defined on a set <m>X</m>, where <m>X</m> is a union of intervals. We say <m>f</m> is <term>differentiable on <m>X</m></term> if it is differentiable at all points of <m>X</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We say <m>f</m> is <term>differentiable</term> if it is differentiable on its entire domain.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>


  <definition xml:id="d_derivative_on_a_domain">
    <title>Derivative of a function</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> be differentiable on <m>X</m>, where <m>X</m> is a union of intervals. The <term>derivative of <m>f</m> on <m>X</m></term> is the function
        <md>
          <mrow>f'\colon X \amp\rightarrow \mathbb{R} </mrow>
          <mrow> x\amp\mapsto f'(x) </mrow>
        </md>
        that assigns to each input <m>x\in X</m> the derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>x</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <definition xml:id="d_higher_order_derivatives">
    <title>Higher order derivatives</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> and <m>f'</m> be differentiable on the set <m>X</m>. The <term>second derivative of <m>f</m></term>, denoted <m>f''</m>, is the derivative of <m>f'</m>: <ie />,
        <me>
          f''=(f')'=\frac{d}{dx}(f')
        </me>
        for all <m>x\in X</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        More generally, let <m>n\geq 1</m> be an integer. The <m>n</m>-th derivative of <m>f</m> is the function obtained from <m>f</m> by applying the derivative operation <m>n</m> times in succession, assuming the relevant derivatives all exist. For small <m>n</m> we denote the <m>n</m>-th derivative with prime notation: <eg />
        <md>
          <mrow> f' \amp=\frac{d}{dx}(f) </mrow>
          <mrow>f''\amp=\frac{d}{dx}(f') </mrow>
          <mrow> f'''\amp=\frac{d}{dx}(f'') </mrow>
        </md>.
        For larger <m>n</m> we denote the <m>n</m>-th derivative of <m>f</m> as <m>f^{(n)}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        A function <m>f</m> is <term><m>n</m>-times differentiable</term> on <m>X</m> if the <m>n</m>-th derivative of <m>f</m> exists for all <m>x\in X</m>. The function <m>f</m> is <term><m>C^n</m> on <m>X</m></term> if <m>f^{(n)}</m> is continuous on <m>X</m>.  
      </p>


    </statement>
  </definition>
</section>
